Very basic &amp; yet pretty interesting question. Here are my findings:

HTML(name attribute)  -&gt;  PHP(its name in `$_POST` or `$_GET`)

&gt; ```
&gt; &quot;My Input&quot; -&gt; &quot;My_Input&quot;
&gt; &quot;My&amp;#32;Input&quot; -&gt; &quot;My_Input&quot;
&gt; &quot;My+Input&quot; -&gt; &quot;My+Input&quot;
&gt; &quot;My-Input&quot; -&gt; &quot;My-Input&quot;
&gt; &quot;My%20Input&quot; -&gt; &quot;My%20Input&quot;
&gt; &quot;My&amp;nbsp;Input&quot; -&gt; &quot;My\u00a0Input&quot;
&gt; ```

So, it looks like no space is allowed, however, [there&#39;s an answer on SO][1] that provides a hack in case you really do want to have a space in the name.

HTML:
```HTML
name=&quot;data[My Input]&quot;
```

PHP:
```PHP
// Inside $_POST
&quot;data&quot; =&gt; [&quot;My Input&quot; =&gt; &quot;Joe&quot;]
```

Here is [another SO answer][2] that explains the observed behaviour.

However, until you are not forced to work with `$_POST` for a very specific reason, you may simply use &amp; safely modify another array. For instance:

```PHP
// Hard copy $_POST
$postData = $_POST;
// Keys with spaces are allowed
$postData[&#39;My Input&#39;] = $postData[&#39;My_Input&#39;];
// Unset keys you don&#39;t like
unset($postData[&#39;My_Input&#39;]);
```

  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/34464498/9430588
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/17092455/9430588

